{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"09c6db77-f9d4-414f-8282-ce096a2f7d43","content":"After a .NET SDK update, use **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\nHere's the difference:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. This is what you want after an SDK update, since the workload versions need to align with the new SDK.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs/fixes corrupted workload installations *at their current versions*. It doesn't upgrade anything — it just repairs broken installs.\n\n**TL;DR:** `dotnet workload update` brings workloads in sync with your new SDK. `dotnet workload repair` only fixes a broken install without changing versions.\n\nIf `update` alone doesn't fix it, also try:\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui\n```\nto ensure the MAUI workload is explicitly installed for the new SDK band.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"36f84b3d-ce79-48ce-9768-add841df9c3c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix a .NET MAUI build issue after an SDK update. This is a general knowledge question I can answer directly without needing tools.","outputTokens":278,"requestId":"D442:21BACA:1BD1EE9:1F61FBC:6A07C0FD"},"id":"130f3d68-86ab-4e19-99be-53474c7ed29c","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:57:41.464Z","parentId":"8697ebfe-543e-44a8-8a7f-63073b67ccee"}
